I'm using verilator for some third party design. Unfortunately, the final linking step stops with an error because a symbol (the function `Vdecap_with_support_tb___024root___eval_initial__TOP__0`) is defined multiple times.

In file `Vdecap_with_support_tb___024root__DepSet_h6dde8dea__0__Slow.cpp` I found the following implementation:

    VL_ATTR_COLD void Vdecap_with_support_tb___024root___eval_initial__TOP__0(Vdecap_with_support_tb___024root* vlSelf) {
        if (false && vlSelf) {}  // Prevent unused
        Vdecap_with_support_tb__Syms* const __restrict vlSymsp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSelf->vlSymsp;
        VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vdecap_with_support_tb___024root___eval_initial__TOP__0\n"); );
        // Body
       ... here comes the initialization of a RAM block ...
    }

In the file `Vdecap_with_support_tb___024root__DepSet_h6dde8dea__1__Slow.cpp` there is another definition of the same function:

